# Keep pyproject.toml OUT of the deployment.
#
# Vercel's Python builder resolves dependencies from pyproject.toml when it is
# present, in preference to requirements.txt. This project's pyproject declares the
# full DEV dependency set — including scipy (72MB), anthropic, supabase and uvicorn —
# which requirements.txt deliberately excludes, with a comment stating that the
# trimming is what takes the bundle "from ~316MB to well under the limit".
#
# So on Vercel the function was being built at ~316MB against the 250MB serverless
# ceiling. It exceeded the limit, could not start, and returned
# INTERNAL_FUNCTION_INVOCATION_FAILED with NO Python output at all — no traceback,
# because no interpreter ever ran. That silence is what made it look like a code bug
# for several rounds; the build logs were green and the runtime logs were empty.
#
# Excluding it here leaves requirements.txt as the only dependency source for the
# deployment, and changes nothing locally: pyproject still drives uv, pytest and ruff
# on a developer machine, and nothing at RUNTIME reads it.
pyproject.toml
uv.lock

# Not needed by the serverless function.
#
# `backtest/` is deliberately NOT here: api/routers/insights.py imports backtest.runner
# at request time, so excluding it would trade this failure for the next one. Checked
# rather than assumed — the same lazy-import pattern that hid the missing packages from
# Vercel's tracer hides them from a reader skimming the imports at the top of a file.
tests/
docs/
data/raw/
data/backups/
data/decks/
data/standout_cache/
.claude/
